'''Kurihara Shrine''' (栗原神社, くりはらじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Zama City|ja|座間市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zama City|qq=}}, {{ill|Kanagawa Prefecture|ja|神奈川県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanagawa Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan.

== History ==

The shrine was established in {{ill|Tenshō era|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō era|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō (Momoyama period)|qq=}} 1 (1573) when the ancestors of the Ōya family, a prominent landowning family in Nakakurihara, enshrined the {{ill|Ōji Gongen|ja|王子権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōji Gongen|qq=}} deity.<ref name="jinja">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kanagawa-jinja.or.jp/search_dtl.php4?jid=640&cd=1207057&npg=0 |title=栗原神社 |publisher=Kanagawa Prefecture Shrine Office |accessdate=2013-12-16}}</ref> Originally known as '''Ōji Gongen Shrine''', it was a focal point of local worship. In 1873 ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 6), several neighboring shrines, including Kinu Harisha, Nigusai Shrine, Sannō Shrine, Wakamiya Shrine, and Ryūzō Shrine, were merged into Kurihara Shrine, which became the central guardian shrine of the Kurihara area. At this time, the shrine was renamed Kurihara Shrine.<ref name="jinja"/>

=== Modern Period ===
Since the Edo period, the local festival music called "Shimomachi-bayashi" had been performed in the area. Around 1902 (Meiji 35), a new style of festival music was introduced from Hayakawa, Ayase City, into the Kurihara region.<ref name="hayashi">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nponia.com/page14-maturibayasi%28zama%29.htm |title=「祭囃子（かまくら・やたい）」座間市指定無形民俗文化財 |publisher=NPO Archives for Intangible Cultural Heritage |date=2009-11-06 |accessdate=2013-12-16}}</ref> This music is still performed annually at the September festival and was designated an Important Cultural Property by Zama City in 1968 (Shōwa 43).<ref name="bunka">{{Cite web|url=http://www.city.zama.kanagawa.jp/www/contents/1219899063356/index.html |title=市指定重要文化財(天然記念物、無形文化財) |publisher=Zama City |date=2011-05-17 |accessdate=2013-12-16}}</ref>

A notable feature of the shrine's precincts is a large {{ill|Shirakashi|ja|シラカシ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shirakashi|qq=}} tree, estimated to be over 500 years old. This tree was designated a Natural Monument by Zama City in 1978 (Shōwa 53).<ref name="bunka"/>

On March 7, 2013 (Heisei 25), a fire believed to be arson destroyed the shrine office and the kaguraden (sacred stage). Historical documents such as a copy of the "Kurihara Shrine Mirror" were also lost in the blaze.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.kanaloco.jp/localnews/article/1303090006/ |title=座間放火事件：神社神楽殿全焼も関与か、地元から憤りの声 |publisher=Kanagawa Newspaper |date=2013-03-09 |accessdate=2013-12-16}}</ref>
[[ja:栗原神社 (座間市)]]

